school, as well as at home. If one is a Christian, one must be a Christian at school as well as at home. If one is an atheist, one must be an atheist at home as well as at school. Why are we so quick to force people to pretend to be things that they are not? Why are we so quick to make us all hypocrites? &#10;What concerns me more, though, is why prayer is frightening to people? How is a group of students getting together to pray a threat to anyone? If you believe in God, then prayer is good. If you don't believe in God, then they are simply wasting their time (not yours... unless you posted a comment on a forum such as this...). Get over your petty fears. A prayer group, what ever the flavour or denomination, is not going to cause a problem at the school. It is the bigoted and closed minded attitudes of those who disagree with their theology that causes problems. Come on people, grow up and stop being afraid. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1217" language="en" documentId="1374" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="JordanBraun" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/tempers-flare-over-prayer-in-schools-1.1104775" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1374" notes="" title="Tempers flare over prayer in schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="603"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="604" end="1217"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43"/></xmi:XMI>